as always, an inside month is not consistently predictive of the S&P500's price.  However, it can be used to predict your own behavior via a defined/systemized trading plan.  These levels are not subjective, they're not being redrawn. Dive into them, build your plan, and execute.
however, 14 of 16 closed the next month higher and the 2 monthly losers were only -0.60% & -0.17% (the two ugly losers get thrown out). "tis but a scratch".

if we then add 1 more parameter, which is a red inside month that closes within -2% of its monthly low, we're left with 16 samples.   Of those 16, 12 trade < the inside month low the next month, 5 trade > the inside month high & we have 2 outside months.

however, the S&P500's forward 1 month return following red inside months is higher 20 of 24, and 6 in a row, with 2 of the 4 monthly losers being less than 1%. The other 2 losers a bit more ugly (-3.86% & -6.12%).

if we then put some parameters around the inside month we've got 24 that have a negative monthly return.  Of these 24, 16 traded < the inside month low the next month, 10 traded > the inside month high & we have 4 outside months.   Average drawdown/drawup next month? -3.16%/4.51%

So let's get a head start on this inside month stuff just in case, shall we? (jinx here)  First, there's 54 inside months since 1970.   There's then only 2 instances of back to back inside months.   So I think it's safe to say April trades > 2801 or < 2585 (if it holds). #spx
